<h2>The problem with lagging signals</h2>

<p>The standard CS warning system is built on lagging indicators: a missed QBR, a drop in product usage, a spike in support tickets, an unresponsive champion. By the time these surface, the customer is already somewhere between frustrated and decided. Your team isn't catching risk. It's documenting it after the fact.</p>

<p>The intervention math is stark. A save play executed 90 days before renewal has a meaningfully higher success rate than one executed 30 days out, which is better than one after a churn notice. Yet most teams are structured, consciously or not, to trigger action at the late stage. The tools flag what's already broken. Nobody is watching what's about to break.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p>At Suki AI, I inherited a $3.2M ARR portfolio where churn was being detected at the "unhappy customer" stage rather than the "activation gap" stage. Building a framework that caught at-risk signal gaps in Salesforce during the first 90 days of deployment shifted intervention timing from reactive to predictive, and drove clinical activation from 24% to 59% across the portfolio.</p>
</div>

<p>The core shift is from monitoring outcomes to monitoring trajectories. Outcomes are what happened. Trajectories are where things are heading. Early signal architecture is built on trajectories.</p>

