<h2>Implementation notes</h2>

<p>Building this architecture from scratch requires three prerequisites before you touch tooling. First, a segment definition with a clear average TTV and activation milestone map for each segment. Without a benchmark, there is no trajectory to measure against. Second, a CRM that captures activity data with enough fidelity to detect engagement patterns, not just closed/won stages. Third, a documented success plan template that ties customer milestones to the signal thresholds above.</p>

<p>At Pointcare, this architecture lives inside a multi-signal customer journey model in Salesforce that surfaces risk scores automatically. At Suki AI, I built an earlier version of it manually, using a combination of Salesforce activity fields and a weekly scoring review. Both versions produced meaningful early churn reduction. The tooling matters less than the discipline of defining the signals, setting the thresholds, and closing the loop between signal and intervention.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p>One practical note for regulated environments: your signal architecture needs to be designed with audit defensibility in mind. Every intervention trigger should have a documented rationale, and every save play should be logged with timestamps and outcome notes. In healthcare SaaS, this isn't optional. It's also good practice. Teams that document intervention logic improve it faster than teams that don't.</p>
</div>

<p>The goal of this framework is not zero churn. It's earlier churn, where you have the most leverage, the lowest intervention cost, and the highest probability of a successful outcome. Start with two or three high-weight signals, set your thresholds, and build the habit of weekly review before you automate. The system gets better the more consistently it's used.</p>

